<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910605-0032</DOCNO><DOCID>910605-0032.</DOCID><HL>   Semel, CEF Firms,   Traders Indicted   On Fraud Charges   ----   By Wade Lambert   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>06/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C20</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>COMMODITIES MARKET (CMD)SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   NEW YORK -- A federal grand jury indicted commoditiestraders Semel andamp; Co. and CEF andamp; Co., on various fraud andconspiracy charges for allegedly squeezing customers out ofpotential profits in precious-metals trades.   The firms are members of the Commodity Exchange in NewYork. Also named were Preston H. Semel, majority partner inSemel and Co.; Charles E. Federbush, a former vice chairman ofthe Commodity Exchange and president of CEF; and MichaelRenner, a Semel floor broker. The 60-count indictment chargesthem with commodities fraud, mail fraud, wire fraud andconspiracy.</LP><TEXT>   The allegations against Mr. Semel and Mr. Federbush aresimilar to those made in a civil lawsuit filed last month bythe Commodity Futures Trading Commission. In the civillawsuit, the commission alleged that the defendants' schemecaused more than $190,000 in customer losses.   The indictment accuses the defendants of conspiring tosteal trading profits and profitable investment opportunitiesfrom customers of Semel andamp; Co. and CEF. The indictment alsoalleges that the defendants transferred trading losses andunfavorable market risks to customers. Further, it accusesthem of altering and destroying trading records to concealtheir actions and other violations of Comex rules.   The alleged illegal trading in gold and silver futurescontracts occurred between September 1986 and June 1988, theindictment said.   The indictment said the defendants traded illegally inconnection with customers' orders, making their own personaltrades, for instance, in advance of large customertransactions. As a result, the defendants allegedly profitedfrom the price increase caused by the customer order.   An attorney for Mr. Semel, 41 years old, of Armonk, N.Y.,couldn't be reached for comment. Michael Feldberg, anattorney for Mr. Federbush with the firm Schulte Roth andamp;Zabel, said, &quot;We think the allegations are wrong, and weexpect to contest them vigorously.&quot; Mr. Federbush, 47, of NewYork, was a Comex vice chairman in 1988. Mr. Renner, 37, ofBrooklyn, couldn't be reached.   The defendants each face a five-year prison sentence and a$250,000 fine on each count. The companies each face amaximum penalty of as much as $500,000 if convicted.   Mr. Semel was charged with 20 counts of commodities fraud,17 counts of mail fraud, and 18 counts of wire fraud. Theindictment accuses Mr. Federbush of 10 counts of commoditiesfraud, nine counts of mail fraud and nine counts of wirefraud. Mr. Renner is charged with one count each ofcommodities fraud, mail fraud and wire fraud. Each of thedefendants is also charged with conspiracy.   Both Mr. Semel and Mr. Federbush have had previous legaltroubles involving commodities transactions. In 1989, Mr.Semel was charged by Comex with fraudulent trading andimproper conduct and was fined $550,000. Mr. Federbush in1986 consented to a CFTC cease-and-desist order stemming fromagency charges that he violated commodity laws dealing withsupervision of customer accounts and capital provisions.   A spokesman for Comex declined to comment on theindictment.</TEXT></DOC>